---
import { CacheSimulator, CpuPipeline, StorageComparison } from "@vislab/react";
import Layout from "../../layouts/vislab-page.astro";
---

<Layout title="Storage latency you can feel">
  <article class="prose">
    <p>
      Static diagrams struggle to convey <em>how much</em> slower a disk seek is
      than an L1 hit. Video helps, but is heavy and hard to scrub while reading.
      Below, VisLab Widgets run a relative latency race in your browser.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <StorageComparison client:visible />
      <figcaption>
        Tokens race from the CPU outward. Faster tiers finish first — ratios are
        pedagogical, not a micro-benchmark of your laptop.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Why this matters for blogs</h2>
    <p>
      When you teach databases or systems, readers need temporal intuition. An
      interactive race they can slow to 0.1× beats a static bar chart for
      “feel,” while staying lighter than a multi-megabyte MP4.
    </p>

    <h2>Related widgets</h2>
    <figure>
      <CacheSimulator client:visible />
      <figcaption>Cache hierarchy hits and misses (LRU / FIFO).</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <CpuPipeline client:visible />
      <figcaption>Five-stage pipeline with simplified hazard stalls.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Source and embeds:
      <a href="https://github.com/mohitmishra786/vislab">VisLab Widgets on GitHub</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .prose {
    max-width: 48rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 2rem 1rem 4rem;
    font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: #e4e4e7;
    background: #0a0a0a;
    min-height: 100vh;
  }
  .prose h1,
  .prose h2 {
    font-family: "JetBrains Mono", ui-monospace, monospace;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .prose a {
    color: #00e5ff;
  }
  .prose figure {
    margin: 2rem 0;
  }
  .prose figcaption {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    opacity: 0.85;
  }
</style>
